    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:137a78df-e044-47d3-93fb-aa14ca0faeae",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 50-year-old man who appears slightly overweight but generally well, with a sedentary office-worker build and mild central adiposity. He is neatly dressed, attentive, and speaks comfortably, though he admits he has not been as proactive about preventive health as he should be. He does not have acute physical complaints and was prompted to seek medical follow-up after routine blood work at an employer-sponsored health screening showed elevated cholesterol levels. He denies chest pain, exertional dyspnea, claudication, focal neurologic deficits, prior stroke, or recent weight loss. On further questioning, he mentions small yellowish plaques near the inner corners of both upper eyelids that have been present for the past 1-2 years and that he assumed were just a cosmetic change; examination is also notable for a faint corneal arcus, findings that can be seen with dyslipidaemia. He reports increasing worry after seeing his cholesterol numbers and his father's early heart disease, and says he is afraid of “having a heart attack like my dad did” if he does not make changes soon. His clinician explains that high LDL and triglyceride levels contribute over time to atherosclerotic plaque formation even when a person feels entirely well, and that this gradual atherosclerosis can eventually lead to coronary disease or ischemic stroke if left untreated.\n\nHe works as a regional sales manager, spending long hours driving and sitting at a computer, often eating meals on the go. His diet is heavy in red meat, takeout food, refined carbohydrates, and late-night snacks, with inconsistent intake of fruits and vegetables. He drinks alcohol socially, usually several beers on weekends, and does not smoke currently, though he smoked briefly in his early 20s. Exercise is sporadic; he occasionally plays golf and walks the dog but does not engage in regular aerobic activity.\n\nAt home, {patientName} lives with his spouse and stays close with two teenage children. He describes his life as busy and somewhat stressful, with work deadlines limiting sleep and making it easy to skip routine clinic visits. He enjoys watching sports, grilling, and weekend home projects; these social routines often center on barbecued fatty meats, processed snacks, and beer, which reinforce the dietary pattern contributing to his lipid disorder. Friends describe him as dependable and sociable, though he acknowledges that many of his social activities revolve around food and alcohol.\n\nOverall, {patientName} gives the impression of a middle-aged man with cardiometabolic risk shaped more by lifestyle than by acute illness. He is concerned because his father had heart disease at a relatively young age and high cholesterol, and he has begun to notice that his belt size has increased over the past decade. He has no known clinical atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease and no history of ischemic stroke, but he is motivated to avoid these complications and is unsure how much can be achieved with diet and exercise alone."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
